Beijing's natural ecology continues to improve, attracting more than 500 species of wild animals to "settle" in the city - chinanews.com
2020-07-26 05: 03: 17 Source: Beijing Youth Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The capital's natural ecology continues to improve to attract wild animal cities to "settle"
There are more than 500 species of wild animals in Beijing
News from our newspaper (Reporter Wang Bin) A reporter from the Beijing Youth Daily learned from the Municipal Landscaping Bureau that in recent years, with the continuous improvement of the capital's natural ecological environment, the types and numbers of wild animals have continued to increase.
At present, the number of terrestrial spine wild animals that inhabit Beijing has increased to more than 500 species, including national first-class protected animals such as brown horse chicken and black stork, as well as national second-class protected animals such as gazelle, big swan, gray crane, and mandarin duck.
Whether it is planted into the urban forests in the second ring, or the small wetlands embedded in the buildings, it not only brings the wild interest of nature to the citizens of the capital, but also attracts wild animals to "settle" in the city.
In the midsummer season, the Songshan National Nature Reserve, located in the Yanshan Mountains in the northwest of Yanqing District, is full of vitality.
A raccoon was playing leisurely by the mountain stream, and two dog badgers were fighting each other.
Looking back, a wild boar can't help but scratch its body and is rubbing against the bark. Hu Qiaoli, director of the Songshan National Nature Reserve Management Office, introduced that as of the end of 2019, in this green sea with a total area of more than 6,200 hectares, there are 178 species of wild animals, including the national first-level protected animal golden eagle and the national second-level protected animal spoon chicken and antelope. Nearly one-third of the city's wild animal species can be seen here.
"In Songshan, wild animals are the real 'owners', and our staff can only be regarded as' bodyguards' at best."
Hu Qiaoli said that in order to understand the situation of wild animals and plants in the reserve on the ground, there are more than 30 professional rangers every day, patrolling along 16 carefully designed protection routes, and there will be a "big circle" every month, spending a whole day walking almost the entire reserve.
"During the inspection, it is not only necessary to check and record biodiversity, but also to inspect and install artificial bird nests, rescue injured wild animals, install field infrared cameras, etc."
Songshan National Nature Reserve has now installed more than 200 infrared cameras to record the living conditions of wild animals in the forest.
Hu Qiaoli introduced that with the continuous enrichment of biodiversity in the reserve in recent years, more and more wild animals have appeared in the lens. The leopard cat, raccoon and pig badger have become "resident guests", and the "appearance rate" of the national second-level protected animal antelope is also getting higher and higher.
Zhang Zhiming, director of the Wildlife and Wetland Protection Division of the Beijing Municipal Bureau of Landscaping, introduced that the number of terrestrial spine wild animals in Beijing has increased from 461 species in 1994 to more than 500 now. The types and numbers of wild animals in Beijing have continued to increase in recent years.
The presence of wild animals in cities is becoming more common, which is closely related to the continuous upgrading of the greening of the capital city in recent years.
In particular, the new round of afforestation and greening construction of one million acres, which began in 2018, proposes to reshape the urban ecological environment, improve the ecological function of woodland green space, and highlight the concept of "near nature".
The planning strives to achieve interconnection and interaction with the surrounding green spaces to facilitate wild animals to "visit relatives and friends", and the trees planted are also honey sources and food plants that animals love.
I work on helping computers communicate with the world around us.
There are many ways to do this, and I like to focus on helping computers to talk about what they see and understand.
Given a scene like this, a modern computer vision algorithm can tell you that there's a woman and there's a dog.
It can tell you that the woman is smiling.
It might even be able to tell you that the dog is very cute.
I work on this problem thinking about how humans understand and live with the world.
The thoughts, memories and stories that a scene like this might evoke for humans.
All the interconnections of related situations.
Maybe you've seen a dog like this before, or you've spent time running on a beach like this one, and that further evokes memories and thoughts of past vacations, past times to the beach, times spent running around with other dogs.
One of my guiding principles is that by helping computers to understand what it's like to have an experience, to understand what we believe and feel in common, then we're in a position to start evolving computer technology in a way that's complementary to our experiences.
So, digging deeper into this, a few years ago I began working on helping computers to produce human-like stories from sequences of images.
So one day, while I was working on my computer, I asked it what it thought about a trip to Australia.
It took a look at the pictures and saw a koala.
It didn't know what the koala was, but it said it thought it was an interesting-looking creature.
Then I shared with the computer a series of images of a house burning down.
The computer took a look at the picture and it said, "This is an amazing view! This is spectacular!"
It sent chills down my spine.
The computer saw a terrible, life-changing and life-destroying event and thought it was a positive thing.
I realized that the computer recognized the contrast between red and yellow and thought it was something worthy of a positive review.
Part of the reason is because most of the images I put into the computer are positive images.
That's because people tend to share positive images when they talk about their experiences.
When was the last time you saw a selfie at a funeral?
I realized that in the process of improving AI, it was task by task, dataset by dataset, creating huge gaps, flaws and blind spots in the understanding of computers.
And while doing so, I was coding for all sorts of biases.
Prejudice reflects a limited view, and it comes from a single dataset -- one that reflects what humans share, such as prejudice and stereotyping.
I thought back to the evolution of the technology that brought me to where I was that day -- that the first color images were calibrated against a white woman's skin, meaning that color photography was biased against black faces.
And that same bias, that blind spot continued into the '90s.
The same blind spot exists even today in how well we recognize the faces of different people in facial recognition technology.
In today's research, I think of state-of-the-art technology that tends to limit our thinking to one dataset and one problem.
And in doing so, we're creating more blind spots and biases that can be further amplified when using artificial intelligence.
I realized then that we had to think deeply about how the technology we invent today will be viewed in five to ten years.
In the interaction between humans and the environment, humans take time to correct problems, so evolution is slow.
Artificial intelligence, by contrast, is evolving at an incredible rate.
And that means that it really matters that we think about this carefully now -- reflect on our own blind spots, our own biases, and consider how that's affecting the technology we're creating now, and discuss what today's technology will mean for the future.
CEOs and scientists have weighed in on what they think about the future of AI.
Stephen Hawking warns that "Artificial intelligence could end mankind."
Elon Musk warns that this is an existential risk and one of the greatest risks we face as a civilized society.
Bill Gates pointed out, "I don't understand why people aren't more worried about artificial intelligence."
But these views -- they're part of the story.
The math, the models, the basic building blocks of artificial intelligence are something that we can all access and use.
We have open-source tools to learn machines and make our own contributions at the same time.
And beyond that, we can share our experiences.
We can share in terms of technology and how it relates to us, and how it excites us.
We can discuss what we love.
We can communicate with the foreseeable future, and that might be more beneficial in terms of technology, or there might be more problems over time.
If we all focus on opening up the discussion on AI and looking to the future, this will help create a general conversation and awareness about what AI is, what it can become, and all the things we need to do to achieve the results that best suit us.
We already see and know this in the technology we use today.
We use smartphones, digital assistants and automatic vacuum cleaners.
Are they evil?
Maybe sometimes.
Are they beneficial?
Yes, they are, too.
They're not exactly the same.
And there you already see the light of the future.
The future continues on from what we build and create right now.
We set in motion the domino effect, which uncovers the evolutionary path of artificial intelligence.
In our time, we shape the AI of tomorrow.
Technology that immerses us in augmented reality, bringing to life the world of the past.
Technology helps people to share their experiences when they have difficulty communicating.
Technology built on online visual media that can be used in self-driving cars.
Technology that produces language based on the understanding of images can evolve into technology that helps the visually impaired to have a better understanding of the visual world.
We also see how technology can lead to problems.
We have technology today that analyzes the physical characteristics of our birth -- such as the color of our skin or the look on our face -- to determine whether we're criminals or terrorists.
We have the technology to process data, process data about gender or race, to determine if we can get a loan.
All that we see now is a snapshot of the evolution of artificial intelligence.
Because where we are now is a moment in evolution.
This means that what we do now will affect the future of things and the world of the future.
If we want AI to evolve in a way that helps humans, we need to define strategies and goals that enable that path right away.
What I want to see is the direction of development that suits human culture and the environment.
Technology can help us heal people with neurological conditions or other disabilities and make life equally challenging for everyone.
Technology that works regardless of your characteristics or the color of your skin.
What I focus on today is the technology of tomorrow and 10 years from now.
Artificial intelligence can turn out in many different ways.
But in this case, it's not a driverless car without any destination.
This is the car that we can drive at the same time.
We choose when to speed up and when to slow down.
We choose if we need to make a turn.
We choose what the AI of the future will be.
There will be a vast playing field where artificial intelligence can be everything.
It will become a lot of different things.
Now it's up to us to figure out what we need to put in place to ensure that the results of artificial intelligence will be better for all of us.
Thank you.
(Applause)
Black land "planted" out of agricultural modernization - Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Harbin, July 26
In the midsummer, two spraying planes passed by the 10,000 mu high-yield demonstration field at the second operation station of the fifth management area of Friendship Farm, forming two white lines, and the big words "the first field in the world" planted with black rice seedlings in the green field stand out.
Kong Lingqiang, director of this operation station, said that this kind of plane can spray more than 6,000 acres of arable land a day, and the efficiency is about 8 times that of drones and hundreds of times that of humans.
This farm is located in Youyi County, Heilongjiang Province, my country's largest grain-producing province. From the sound of rice cutting in the past to the sound of "rumbling" motors today, traditional Chinese farming and farms have been transformed on this black soil belt.
In addition to airplanes, satellites are also used in the modern agricultural production of Friendship Farm.
Kong Lingqiang introduced that on the one hand, they use satellite remote sensing technology to achieve precise fertilization, reduce agricultural input, and reduce pollution; on the other hand, satellite navigation technology can improve the level of standardized agricultural machinery field operations.
In this year's rice production process, the farm expanded the operating area of satellite navigation unmanned rice transplanting technology from 3,000 mu last year to 30,000 mu.
This technology makes the planting of seedlings more uniform, maximizes the use of sunlight and arable land resources, and saves 16 yuan in labor costs per mu.
The farm tried new technologies such as informatization and intelligence in agricultural production, forming the largest agricultural machinery group in my country from the ground to the sky.
According to statistics, the total number of farm agricultural machinery currently stands at 49,000 units (pieces), and the comprehensive mechanization rate in the field has reached 99.8%.
Agricultural machinery operations achieve 100% GPS satellite navigation, 100% precision sowing in dry fields, and 100% operation in dry fields.
"Green agriculture, smart agriculture, and digital agriculture are the direction of agricultural modernization."
Liu Hualien, director of Friendship Farm, said.
The key to agricultural modernization lies in scientific and technological progress.
Heilongjiang Agricultural Reclamation, represented by farms, has played a demonstration and leading role in modern large-scale agriculture "aircraft carrier" in recent years, and has initially established a modern agricultural industry system dominated by large-scale planting, standardized production, and industrial management.
On the outskirts of Youyi County, there is an Agricultural Machinery Expo Park covering an area of 350,000 square meters.
Here is a centralized exhibition of more than 140 agricultural machinery and tools introduced and used by Heilongjiang Agricultural Reclamation over the years.
These agricultural machinery and farms have witnessed the development of China's agricultural modernization.
Small Home for All-Jiangkouhe Lianhe, Hefei, Anhui, Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Hefei, July 26 Title: Offering a small family home for everyone — the transfer of the masses in the Jiangkouhe Lianwei, Hefei, Anhui Province
Xinhua News Agency reporters Chen Shangying, Wang Liwu, Liu xiacun
At more than 4: 00 pm on July 25, Fu Kunbao, wearing rubber shoes covered with mud, went from the former house to the back room, and his wife Zhou Yan came back and forth busy packing things.
"When I received a call from a village cadre to transfer, I was still weeding in the field."
Fu Kunbao said that he has transferred more than 60 acres of land and planted rice, and is now growing well. "I also took medicine yesterday, and I haven't packed my tools yet."
Fu Kunbao pointed to the pesticide sprayer placed in the corner. "No one wants his home to be flooded, leave a small home for everyone."
In response to the continued high water level pressure and possible heavy rainfall in Chaohu Lake, Hefei City, Anhui Province, is preparing to open the Jiangkouhe Lianhe flood distribution and water storage at Fu Kunbao's home on the 26th.
Jiangkouhe Lianwei is located in Feixi County, next to the Chaohu dike.
There are thousands of villagers involved in Yan Dian Township and Sanhe Town in the polder who need to be transferred.
As of 16: 00 on the 25th, the water level of Chaohu Lake, my country's fifth largest freshwater lake, remained at a high level of 13.2 meters, 0.7 meters above the guaranteed water level.
Fu Kunbao's kitchen is clean and tidy. There is a pot of pumpkin head vegetables on the table, and there are eggs and some brine in the refrigerator.
"I didn't expect to move. The water in Jiangkouhe looks good at present."
Zhou Yan said that the home is a bungalow, and some large objects have not yet figured out where to put them.
"Pack up your valuables first, and large items such as refrigerators and televisions can be placed in the homes of high-lying neighbors or relatives for the time being."
Wang Lili, a village cadre, gave Fu Kunbao an idea.
Wang Lixi is responsible for the transfer and resettlement of 13 villagers, and notifies each household to confirm each person's resettlement plan.
The nearest resettlement site to Fu Kunbao's family is Su Primary School in Yan Dian Township, about 2 kilometers away.
In addition to the large items, Fu Kunbao and his wife have a headache with more than 1,000 kilograms of grain in the family and some newly bought furniture.
"The grain is ready to be dragged to a relative's house, and the furniture can't be moved."
As soon as the couple discussed, they put a stool under the newly bought bed and raised the bed by about half a meter.
At 6 pm, Fu Kunbao began to use a tricycle to transport things to relatives' homes. Zhou Yan continued to clean up at home.
At more than 11 o'clock in the evening, the couple looked back and forth at home, pulled the switch, and were ready to go to the resettlement site.
"I hope the water will retire early."
Fu Kunbao said.
At 9: 30 am on July 26, the reporter saw at the scene of Jiangkouhe Lianhe that the local area had made various preparations before flood distribution.
