You all know the truth of what I'm going to say.
I think the intuition that inequality can cause social fragmentation and corruption has been around since before the French Revolution.
The difference is that we can now find evidence that we can compare societies, societies with different levels of equality, to understand the effects of inequality.
I'm going to show you some data and explain why that data is actually related.
But first, let's see how miserable our lives are.
(Laughter) I'd like to start my speech with a paradox.
This shows you life expectancy in relation to gross national income -- how rich countries are on average.
You see the countries on the right, like Norway and the United States, are twice as rich as Israel, Greece, Portugal on the left.
But that doesn't affect their life expectancy.
There's no suggestion of a relationship.
But if we look within our societies, we can see that there are huge differences in health within their entire societies.
This is still life expectancy.
These are small towns in England and Wales -- the poorest on the right, the richest on the left.
There's a big difference between the poor and the rest of us.
Even the people just below the top have poorer health than the people at the top.
So income means a lot in our societies, but it doesn't make sense in comparison between societies.
The explanation of that paradox is that, in our societies, we're looking at relative income or social status, social status -- where we are in relation to each other and the size of the differences between us.
As soon as you have that idea, you should immediately wonder: What happens if the gap widens, what if it narrows, widens or narrows the income gap?
That's what I'm going to tell you.
I'm not using any hypothetical data.
My data comes from the United Nations -- like the World Bank -- on the income differences between these rich, developed market democracies.
The method we use, simple and easy to understand, and you can download it, is to compare the income differences between the top 20 percent and the bottom 20 percent in each country.
You can see that the countries on the left are more equal -- Japan, Finland, Norway, Sweden -- and the top 20 percent are about 3.5 to 4 times as rich as the bottom 20 percent.
But on the more unequal end -- U.K., Portugal, USA, Singapore -- the income differences are twice as large.
In this way, our country (the UK) is twice as unequal as some of the other successful democratic markets.
Now I'm going to show you what that does to our societies.
We collected data on problems with social gradients, which are more common at the bottom of the social ladder.
Internationally comparable data include life expectancy, children's maths and literacy scores, infant mortality rates, suicide rates, proportion of the population in prison, teenage pregnancy rates, levels of trust, obesity, mental illness -- which in standard diagnostic classification includes drug and alcohol addiction -- and social mobility.
We put all of this into one coefficient.
They're all weighted equally.
A country's score is the average of these factors.
As you can see, these scores are related to the inequality comparison I've just shown you, and I'm going to show that data over and over again.
The more unequal countries do worse on all kinds of social problems.
There's a very strong correlation.
But if you look at the same index of health and social problems in relation to gross national income per capita and gross national income, there's nothing there, no correlation anymore.
We were a little bit worried that people might think that we were choosing specific problems to suit our theories and then artificially creating evidence, so we also published a paper in the British Medical Journal on the UNICEF index of child well-being.
It has 40 different parts, summed up by others.
It includes whether children can talk to their parents, whether they have books at home, what immunization rates are, and whether there's bullying at school.
Everything goes into it.
So that's how the index relates to the same level of inequality.
Children do worse in the more unequal societies.
Highly significant relationship.
But again, if you look at the relationship between child well-being and national income per capita, you're going to get nowhere. There's no suggestion of a relationship.
All the data I've shown you so far reveals the same thing.
The average well-being of our societies is no longer dependent on national income and economic growth.
They're very important in poorer countries, but not in the rich developed world.
And the differences between us and where we are in relation to each other now seem very important.
Now I'm going to show you some of the parts of our index.
This is the mutual trust index.
It's the proportion of the population who agree that most people can be trusted.
This is data from the World Values Survey.
You see, on the more unequal side, about 15 percent of the population feel they can trust others.
But in the more equal societies, it rises to 60 or 65 percent.
If you look at measures of participation in community activities or social capital, there are very similar relationships closely related to inequality.
I would say, we did this work twice.
We did it first on these rich developed countries, and then we changed the test and repeated it on the 50 American states -- asking the same question: Do the more unequal states do worse on all of these measures?
This is the relationship between trust and inequality in a general social survey conducted by the federal government.
Very similar scatter over a similar range of levels of trust.
The same thing is going on.
Basically we found that almost all of the factors related to trust that are reflected in international surveys are also reflected in the 50 states that we surveyed separately.
This is no coincidence.
This is mental illness.
The World Health Organization collects data using the same diagnostic interviews on random samples that allow us to compare rates of mental illness in each society.
This is the proportion of the population with any mental illness in the previous year.
It goes from about 8 percent to more than 24 percent -- which means that society as a whole is three times as likely to have mental illness as any other society.
Again, these are closely related to inequality.
This is the crime rate.
The red dots are American states, and the blue triangles are Canadian provinces.
But look at the differences in their numbers.
The murder rate goes from 15 homicides per million up to 150.
This is the proportion of the population in prison.
This is a tenfold difference, and the exponential function will magnify the difference.
But the changes in the prison population range from 40 to 400.
Crime is not the main reason for this relationship.
In some places, crime can explain part of the reason.
But it's more about harsher sentencing, or harsher sentencing.
The more unequal societies are more likely to retain the death penalty.
This is children dropping out of high school.
Again, there's a big difference.
If we discuss the selection of social talents, we can see that this gap is very damaging.
This is social mobility.
It's actually a measure of mobility based on income.
Basically, it's asking: Do rich fathers have rich sons and poor fathers have poor sons, or is there no relationship between the two?
On the more unequal side, fathers' income is more important -- in the U.K., USA.
And in northern Europe, fathers' income is less important.
There's more social mobility.
As we often say -- and I know there are a lot of Americans in the audience here -- if Americans want to realize their "American dream", they should go to Denmark.
(Laughter) (Applause) I've shown you in italics here.
I can also show you some other problems.
Those problems are more common at the bottom of the social gradient.
But there are endless problems with social gradients that are worse in unequal countries -- not just a little bit worse, but anything from twice as common to 10 times as common.
Think of the expense, the human cost.
I'd like to go back to this graph that I showed you earlier where we put it all together to make two points.
First, in graph after graph, we find that the countries that do worse, whatever the outcome, seem to be the more unequal ones, but the ones that do well seem to be the Nordic countries and Japan.
So what we're looking at is the relationship between general social disorder and inequality.
It's not just one or two things that go wrong, it's almost everything.
The other very important point I'd like to make on this graph is that if you look at the bottom, Switzerland and Japan, they're very different countries in all sorts of ways.
The status of women, the extent to which they stick to the nuclear family, are at two extremes in the rich developed world.
But another very important difference is how they achieve greater equality.
Sweden has big differences in income, but it uses taxes, state benefits, generous benefits and so on to close the gap.
Japan is rather different.
First of all, Japan has a smaller pre-tax wage gap.
It has lower taxes.
It also has a smaller welfare state.
And in our study of the American states, we find a stark contrast.
Some states do well through redistribution, while others do well because they have smaller income differences before tax.
So we conclude that it doesn't matter how you achieve greater equality, what matters is that you can achieve that equality.
I'm not talking about complete equality, I'm talking about what does exist in rich developed market democracies.
Another surprising thing about this graph is that it's not just the poor who are affected by inequality.
There seems to be some truth in John Donne's words: "No man is an island."
Through a series of studies, we can compare the behavior of people at each social level in more or less equal countries.
This is just one example.
This is infant mortality.
According to the British General Socio-Economic Classification, some Swedes very kindly classified a lot of infant deaths.
This is an anachronistic classification based on fathers' occupations, so single mothers have their own set of data.
But when we look at the so-called "lower social classes", it's unskilled manual work.
In the middle are skilled manual jobs, then advanced non-manual jobs, up to professional jobs -- doctors, lawyers, managers of large companies.
You can see here that Sweden is doing better than Britain, doing better at every level of society.
The biggest differences are at the bottom of society.
But even at the top, living in a more equal society has some advantages.
We showed five different sets of data covering educational outcomes and health in the United States and internationally.
It seems that on the whole -- the more equal societies show the most obvious differences at the bottom, but they also have some advantages at the top.
I should explain what's going on.
I think I'm showing and discussing the psychosocial effects of inequality.
It's more about feelings of superiority and inferiority, being valued and looked down upon, respected and devalued.
Of course, the feelings generated by the competition for status drive the consumerism of society.
But it also leads to status insecurity.
We worry more about how we're judged and seen by others, whether we're attractive, smart, all that sort of thing.
Social-evaluative judgments increase the fear of these social-evaluative judgments.
Interestingly, some similar work is going on in social psychology: Some people reviewed 208 different studies in which volunteers were invited to a psychological laboratory and then tested for their stress levels and their responses to doing stressful tasks.
In this observation, scientists were interested in what kind of stress is most likely to raise levels of cortisol, the most important stress hormone.
The result is tasks that include social-evaluative threats -- tasks that threaten self-esteem and social status -- tasks in which others can negatively judge your performance.
These stresses have a very particular effect on the physiology of stress.
So far we have been criticized.
Of course, there are people who don't like this, and people who find this very surprising.
But I should tell you that when people criticize us for picking and choosing data, we never do so.
We have an unconditional rule that if our data source contains data for the country we're looking at, then we incorporate it into the analysis.
Our data source determines whether the data is valid, not us.
Otherwise it would be biased.
What about other countries?
There are 200 studies of health in relation to income and equality in the academic peer-reviewed journals.
This is not confined to these countries here, but it hides a very simple proof.
The same countries, the same measure of inequality, one problem after another.
Why don't we control other factors?
I've shown you that per capita national income doesn't make any difference.
Of course, others have used more sophisticated methods in the literature to rule out poverty, education and other factors in the experiment.
What about causality?
Correlation in itself does not prove causality.
We spent a good bit of time.
Indeed, people have a good understanding of the causality of our outcomes.
The biggest change in our understanding of the drivers of long-term health in the rich developed world is how important chronic stress from society is affecting the immune system and the cardiovascular system.
Or for example, the reason why violence is becoming more common in more unequal countries is because people are sensitive to being looked down upon.
I would say that in order to solve this problem, we have to deal with the post-tax and pre-tax problems.
We should limit income and curb the bonus culture at the top.
I think we have to do everything we can to hold our leaders accountable to their employees.
I'd like to conclude by saying that we can improve our real quality of life by reducing the differences in income between us.
In this way, we'll find that we've suddenly solved the psychosocial well-being of an entire society, and that's amazing.
Thank you.
