Hoh Xil Tibetan antelope enters the return season - Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Xining, July 25 (Reporter Wang Jinjin) The reporter learned from the Wudaoliang conservation station of the Hoh Xil Management Office, Jiangyuan Park, Director of Sanjiangyuan National Park Management, that monitoring showed that the Tibetan antelopes that had previously migrated to the Zhuonai Lake area in the hinterland of Hoh Xil to give birth are ending their babies and beginning to take their cubs back to their original habitat.
Monitoring footage near the Wudaoliang Conservation Station shows that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelopes led 3 Tibetan antelope cubs through 3002 kilometers of the Qinghai-Tibet Highway and the Wudaoliang North Bridge of the Qinghai-Tibet Railway. The Tibetan antelopes have begun to relocate.
Experts analyze that in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope cubs in the returning flock accounts for a quarter to a fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelope flocks.
Lien Xinming, deputy researcher of the Northwest Plateau Biology Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: "At the beginning of the return, the Tibetan antelope faces a high risk of predation, so the number of cubs in the flock will be relatively small, and there may even be no cubs."
According to statistics from the Hoh Xil Management Office of Jiangyuan Park, Director of Sanjiangyuan National Park Management, the overall number of Tibetan antelopes relocating has been increasing year by year. The number of Tibetan antelopes relocating in 2019 was 4,860, an increase of 338 over 2018.
Liang Xinming said: "It is expected that the return of Tibetan antelopes this year will end in early September, and the number of returning Tibetan antelopes is still expected to continue to increase."
Tibetan antelope is a national first-class protected animal.
At the end of May every year, Tibetan antelopes from Sanjiangyuan in Qinghai, Qiangtang in Tibet, and Aljinshan in Xinjiang all go to Zhuonai Lake in the hinterland of Hoh Xil to give birth.
Wu Xiaomin, an expert in the protection of Tibetan antelopes in my country and a researcher at the Shaanxi Provincial Institute of Zoology (Northwest Endangered Animals Research Institute), said: "The return of Tibetan antelopes is the process of female Tibetan antelopes returning to their habitat after they have given birth. At first, the returning groups that left the breeding grounds were relatively large, but then the Tibetan antelopes will return to their respective habitats according to different geographical populations and along different paths."
In order to ensure the safe relocation of Tibetan antelope flocks, the reporter learned that the Hoh Xil Management Office of Jiangyuan Park, Director of Sanjiangyuan National Park Management, has arranged staff to continuously carry out video monitoring and district patrols in the main relocation area.
If a Tibetan antelope flock is found trying to cross the road, the mountain patrol team will carry out temporary traffic control at the first time to allow the flock to pass through the wildlife passage safely to ensure that it is as little human interference as possible on the way back.
