Graduate art exhibition moved into the shopping mall public welfare exhibition - Xinhuanet
In the "cloud graduation" season of colleges and universities, a rare offline graduate art exhibition opened warmly last weekend.
However, it is neither in the art gallery nor on the campus, but in the public space of Chaoyang Dayue City, and is open to the public for free until August 23.
The reporter learned that this 2020 graduate art exhibition has collected 50 works / groups of 57 young artists from the Central Academy of Fine Arts, China Media University and Tianjin Academy of Fine Arts. The exhibition space extends from the 2nd floor to the 6th floor, and makes full use of the light box in the building to display graphic works to maximize the artistic atmosphere of the graduation season.
Under the epidemic, the significance of this exhibition is particularly special.
Ge Ping, head of beauty Chen in Dayue City, Chaoyang, admitted: "We have chosen to bring the graduation exhibition towards the 'cloud' back to offline space again. We also hope that more people will see young people's exploration of themselves and understanding of the world, and magnify the healing power of art for society and the soul."
She revealed that the works in this exhibition were collected from graduates of several major art colleges, and selected from them suitable for commercial space display. The forms of works range from traditional shelf paintings and sculptures to new media devices, interactive animation, and VR panorama. The volume and richness are the highest in the past year.
Among them, Li Yunxiao expressed his feelings in the epidemic through a mixture of mechanical and manual creative language in "The First Battle of 2020"; Liu Jiaying discussed the themes of "cryptocurrency", "credit creation", and "transaction" through the work "Sound Money" created by the Taifang blockchain; Zhang Jiaqi's "Cat Forest" and Qiu Daqiang's "Bohemian" both show animals that are often accompanied by humans, from which you can see the young artist's understanding of the relationship between humans and animals; and Zhu Zhongyu's work "Winter of Faith-Gift" is a reminder to young people who are growing up, "When one day you succeed in your career, don't forget your original heart, remember that simplicity and sincerity."
Among the few graduates who personally set up the exhibition is Li Jingyin from the Sculpture Department of Tianjin Academy of Fine Arts.
"I came to Beijing on July 7. I was actually a little worried about the epidemic. I also did a nucleic acid test three days in advance. I brought alcoholic cotton and test reports to the exhibition."
His work "Yesterday is a Mystery" has a complex structure and must be done by himself.
At the same time, he also undertakes the task of helping his classmates repair damaged works.
"The cloth exhibition lasted until 4: 30 in the morning, and then it was repaired. The time was very tight. I forgot to take a picture with the work, and I was a little sorry."
He hopes that when the epidemic is more stable, he will come to Beijing with his classmates to see his work exhibition.
