France increases its military investment in space - Xinhuanet
French Defense Minister Florence Parley said on the 24th that France will increase its space defense budget by hundreds of millions of euros to develop space military forces to prevent "unfriendly actions" that other countries may make in outer space.
Parley told the Provence newspaper that between 2019 and 2025, the expenditure budget for French space military projects will increase from the previously proposed 3.6 billion euros (about 4.2 billion US dollars) to 4.3 billion euros (5 billion US dollars).
According to the French Military Planning Act 2019-2025 approved by the French Parliament in 2018, France is expected to update its existing observation satellites and communication satellites in the future, launch three electromagnetic listening satellites, and improve the modernization level of space surveillance radars.
French President Emmanuel Macron announced in July last year that a space military command and an "aviation and space force" will be established within the French Air Force.
Parley said that she will officially announce the establishment of this space force when she visits a military school in Salon, Provence, later.
Parley said that this space force is affiliated with the Air Force and has a strength of 500 by 2025.
She said: "The idea that people used to think that space served the common interests of science is gone forever. Now space is a place for countries to compete for global hegemony."
Parley reiterated Macron's previous statements, saying that France has no intention of provoking an arms race.
"We are by no means engaged in an arms race. But it is my responsibility to fully recognize the threats we may face."
Parley recalled the surveillance of a military satellite shared by France and Italy in 2017.
She said that it was a Russian satellite that "peeped".
Russia denies this statement.
Parley said that France "soon" will have small patrol satellites capable of detecting and locking "the black hands behind those unfriendly actions."
French media believe that the reason why France seeks to establish a space force is due to US President Donald Trump's request in February last year that the US Department of Defense draft a bill to establish a space force.
Trump signed the National Defense Authorization Act in December last year, approving the establishment of the sixth largest military service in the United States, the Space Force.
Some experts worry that these US measures have accelerated the pace of US space militarization and may trigger a new round of space arms race.
