Beijing News (Reporter Liu Zhen) On July 26, the Beijing Philharmonic Chorus published an obituary. The founder of the Beijing Philharmonic Chorus, a well-known Chinese conductor and music educator, and Yang Honggnian, a lifelong academic member of the Central Conservatory of Music and professor of the Department of Command, died in Beijing at 13: 55 on July 26, 2020 at the age of 86.
The picture is from the official website of the Beijing Philharmonic Chorus.
Yang Honggnian was born in 1934, a native of Nanjing, Jiangsu, and has loved music since childhood.
In 1951, he was the conductor of the chorus of Nanjing People's Radio Station. In the autumn of 1951, he was admitted to the Music Department of Shanghai East China Normal University. He studied and directed under Professor Yang Jiaren and German conductor Hitzman, and the former Soviet expert Arzamanov learned the style and polyphony.
In 1958, he taught in the Music Department of Beijing Art Normal College, and in 1973 he was transferred to the Composition Department and Command Department of the Central Conservatory of Music.
Yang Honggnian founded the Beijing Philharmonic Chorus in 1983.
For more than 30 years, with the tenet of "love and dedication", he has led this choir to sing all over the world, and has won dozens of awards in important competitions at home and abroad.
He has directed the performances of more than 30 groups including the Central Orchestra Chorus, the Central National Song and Dance Troupe, the Oriental Song and Dance Troupe, and the Shanghai Chorus, and held many symphony concerts and chorus concerts.
Publications include "Orchestra Training", "Chorus Training", "Two Songs Writing", "Children's Songs" (upper and lower volumes), and papers "On Chorus Phonetic Issues", "On the Sound Hierarchy Layout of Orchestral Music", as well as translations of "Chorus Accessories Law" and "Debussy's Harmony Language".
