At the Bayong Zhuokang sentry point, platoon commander Yu Wang and a soldier were on duty.
In this place where the average annual temperature is more than ten degrees below zero, a row of simple barracks stands at the mountain pass. Not far from the barracks, a national flag is fluttering in the wind. The soldiers are on duty in the wind every day, and they need to regularly patrol higher altitude locations.
The soldiers climbed up the steep slope of the rubble, requiring both hands and feet.
It was late July, when flowers and plants were flourishing in low-altitude areas, and in Bayan Zhuokang, only the ditch behind the barracks had relatively dense green.
Gao Peng, a soldier who has been stationed at the outpost for 6 years, pointed to the ditch and said that this is their back garden. Only in July and August can the grass grow slowly every year. After a while, all turned yellow and covered with snow.
Foot patrols can take about 9 hours.
In the harsh plateau environment, the soldiers stationed here are accompanied by snow-capped mountains and glaciers all year round, and they also regularly patrol the higher mountain passes.
A few days ago, a patrol team composed of 8 soldiers, led by instructor Liang Yixin, once again embarked on the patrol road.
Each soldier carries a weight of about 30 jin and marches towards the target point early in the morning.
On the way, a soldier rebelled, and his comrades gave emergency relief.
In addition to patrol missions, the soldiers at the Baudjokang sentry point have to conduct tactical and physical training every day.
Time passes by, the altitude continues to rise, the oxygen content is getting lower and lower, and the physical strength is constantly overdrawn. These factors test the will of the patrol members.
They clenched their teeth and insisted, crossing several landslide points one after another, and crossing several difficult and dangerous beaches.
At about 16 o'clock, it was lunch time for the patrol members. They took out their own dry food, sat on the spot at an altitude of more than 5,700 meters, accompanied by rain and snow, and supplemented their physical strength with food.
The soldiers at the Bayong Zhuokang sentry point conducted tactical and physical training.
During the break, they will play cards together, and the loser will do push-ups, both for entertainment and physical exercise.
After a short rest in the cold wind, they climbed to the target point of the patrol, took out the national flag on the mountain pass, and made a solemn declaration.
Behind them are the snow-capped mountains, and in front of them are dozens of kilometers of no-man's land. They are the safest guardians of the country.
