Understand what is a professional level difference before volunteering - chinanews.com
2020-07-27 02: 22: 36 Source: Chongqing Morning News Author: Yu Xiao Responsibility Editor: Yu Xiao
Understand what is a professional level difference before volunteering
Every year when you report for the college entrance examination, there are students or parents who do not understand the terms involved in the voluntary reporting, which affects the voluntary reporting.
This year, 5 colleges and universities including Beijing Jiaotong University, Beijing University of Science and Technology, Beijing University of Posts and Telecommunications, Beijing Forestry University, and Beijing University of Chemical Technology jointly issued the 2020 enrollment policy, eliminating the professional level difference.
What is the meaning of professional level difference and what is the significance in voluntary reporting?
There are three ways of professional distribution rules
Experts remind that before filling in the volunteer, you must read the "Admissions Regulations" of your favorite school and understand the admission rules of colleges and universities, including the transfer ratio, professional distribution rules, etc.
The professional allocation rules refer to the three methods of major priority, score priority, and professional level difference for professional admission after colleges and universities are transferred.
Which method is specifically used by colleges and universities will be specified in the "Admissions Regulations".
But there are also some colleges and universities whose admission principle is that the total score is preferred, and there is no level difference between majors.
That is to say, candidates in the admission range will be queued according to the total score. When the score does not reach the first professional volunteer admission score line, it will be determined whether it has reached the second professional volunteer admission score line, so that until the admission to the last professional volunteer, there is no grade difference between the professional volunteers.
The so-called "professional level difference" is that when colleges and universities arrange candidates' majors, they determine the admission majors of volunteer candidates from different majors according to one or several points announced in the admission regulations. This score is the "professional level difference".
That is, the difference between the score of the college when admitting candidates for the first professional volunteer and the non-first professional volunteer, and the grade difference between the professional volunteers, such as 3 points, 2 points, 1 point, etc.
For example.
Suppose that student Xiaoming applied for college A and scored 560 points. His professional volunteers are: Computer, international trade, automation, mechanical engineering, and e-commerce. The professional admission of college A adopts the method of professional grade difference, which is divided into 2 points, 1 point, 1 point, and 0 points.
In the professional assignment, if Xiaoming's first professional volunteer meets the professional admission requirements and the major has a planned balance, then Xiaoming is admitted to the "computer" major; if the computer is not admitted, his score will be subtracted by 2 points. According to the score of 558 points, he will be ranked with the candidates who applied for the "international trade" of the first professional volunteer to determine whether they meet the professional admission requirements; if it is still not met, the score is subtracted by 1 point (that is, 557 points) for the admission of the third professional volunteer "automation"; if it is still not met, the score is subtracted by 1 point (that is, 556 points) for admission to the fourth major. If the follow-up major still fails to meet its professional volunteers, it will no longer be reduced, and so on.
Different universities have different professional level difference settings
With the popularization of parallel volunteering, many colleges and universities have now abolished the professional level difference, but some colleges and universities still retain this method this year. According to the "Admissions Regulations" announced by each school, more than 20 universities have set up professional level differences this year.
For example, Sichuan Agricultural University, Shandong University of Science and Technology, Heilongjiang University of Chinese Medicine, Jiangsu University of Science and Technology, Jiangxi Normal University, Chengdu Medical School, Northeast Electric Power University, Jiemei University, Nanjing Medical University, Nanjing University of Technology, Ningxia University, Shandong University of Technology, China Civil Aviation Flight Academy, etc.
In these colleges and universities, the professional level difference set by each university is different.
Some colleges and universities have a grade difference in each major, such as Ningxia University. Candidates whose files have been submitted to the school are admitted according to the order in which the candidates fill in their professional volunteers.
And some universities have set up different professional level differences between different majors.
For example, at Jiemi University, the total score of the professional volunteer level difference is 4 points, that is, the difference between the first professional volunteer and other professional volunteers is 3 points. There is no level difference between other professional volunteers, which is regarded as parallel volunteers, and the professional level difference between other professional volunteers and transfer professional volunteers is 1 point.
When filling in the volunteer, candidates and parents must carefully read the admission policy of the reported school to see if there is a professional level difference, and what is the form of the grade difference. While fully considering the scores, it is also necessary to reasonably analyze the school and major to be selected. If the college explicitly adopts the grade difference method for admission in the admission charter, candidates should pay attention to the gradient between the majors when choosing a major to improve the admission probability.
